FBIS TRENDS-06APR94-JAPAN-EU 
<H3> <TI>      Japan-EU:  Tokyo Seeks EU Support Against U.S. Trade Policy </TI></H3>

</HEADER>

<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>       Japan-EU:  Tokyo Seeks EU Support Against U.S. Trade Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>



<TEXT>
Recent      Japanese press reporting has suggested that the Japanese 
Government is attempting to enlist the support of the European 
Union (EU) against U.S. efforts to force open Japanese markets, 
particularly Washington's recent revival of the Super 301 
provision of the 1988 Omnibus Trade Bill.  Minister of 
International Trade and Industry Hiroshi Kumagai, for example, 
appears to have used French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe's 31 
March-3 April visit to Tokyo to coordinate Japanese and French 
strategy toward any possible U.S. use of Super 301, which permits 
Washington to identify countries that discriminate against U.S. 
exports and impose sanctions if those countries fail to remove 
barriers to U.S. products.  According to a 1 April Kyodo report, 
Japanese officials reported that during a 1 April meeting, 
Kumagai and Juppe agreed that Tokyo and Paris would "oppose 
unilateral U.S. trade retaliation" such as that mandated by Super 
301.  In comments suggesting that the two countries might attempt 
to lobby against Super 301 during the upcoming 12-15 April 
ministerial conference of the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade (GATT) in Marrakech, Morocco, Juppe reportedly told Kumagai 
that he hoped retaliatory measures, such as Super 301, would be 
abolished after GATT members sign the final accord of the Uruguay 
Round of multilateral trade talks in Marrakech (Kyodo, 1 April). 

   Japanese media reporting about Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata's 
plans for the Marrakech meeting also suggests that Tokyo has been 
lining up European support against Super 301.  According to a 6 
April Kyodo report, an undentified Japanese Government source 
stated that, during meetings with U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor, Hata will urge Washington not to invoke Super 301 
against Japan by citing European and Asian criticism of the 
provision.  Hata may have solicited support from EU Commissioner 
Sir Leon Brittan for this effort when, according to the 29 March 
Mainichi Shimbun, Hata called Brittan on 29 March to explain the 
Japanese market opening package announced that day. 

(AUTHOR:  BOUNDS.  QUESTIONS AND/OR COMMENTS, PLEASE CALL CHIEF, 
ASIA DIVISION ANALYSIS TEAM, (703)-733-6096.) 
EAG/HEBBEL/JF 06/2050Z APR 

</TEXT>

