FBIS TRENDS-06APR94-JORDAN 
<H3> <TI>      New TV News Program, Broadcasting Chief </TI></H3>

</HEADER>

<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>       New TV News Program, Broadcasting Chief </PHRASE></F></HT>



<TEXT>
In   an apparent effort to modernize and expand its Arabic-language 
news programming, state-run Jordan TV recently inaugurated a weekly 
news magazine entitled "60 Minutes," which replaces the station's 
30-minute nightly newscast on Fridays. According to an official 
announcement, the new program is intended "to develop the ordinary 
newscast into a comprehensive, objective, and accurate news magazine 
to keep up with media technology, which is progressing 
continuously" (Jordan TV, 25 March).  To date, programs aired have 
included a "special news report" on Jordanian-Arab relations in the 
wake of King Husayn's recent visits to Oman and Qatar; reports on 
the impact of the UN inspection of ships bound for al-'Aqaba port; 
segments on domestic issues, including features on crime and human 
rights; and a general mix of economic, regional, and international 
news (Jordan TV, 25 March, l April). 
   In an apparently unrelated development, Information Minister 
Jawad al-'Anani announced the retirement of Jordan Radio and 
Television Corporation Director General Radi Alkhas--without further 
comment or explanation--and named Ibrahim Shahzadah as acting head. 
Shahzadah, previously director of Jordan Television, has been 
associated with Jordan radio and television since 1957 (Jordan 
Times, 22 March). 
(AUTHOR:  MURRAY.  QUESTIONS AND/OR COMMENTS, PLEAS CALL CHIEF, NEAR 
EAST ANALYSIS BRANCH, (703) 733-6094.) 
ENEAG/BLOUGH JEG 07/0421Z APR 

</TEXT>

